    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-11-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-11-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="324" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d324">
                <head>No. 324.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bayard</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Anderson</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-11-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 1,
                            1887</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 62.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 156 has been received. In it
                        you state that you have been informed of a movement on the part of Germany
                        which appears to be the beginning of an attempt to influence or compel
                        Denmark to exclude American pork.</p>
                <p>The matter is important, and you are instructed to keep a close watch and
                        report what may transpire.</p>
                <p>Certain executive documents<note n="*" xml:id="d324fn1">Accompaniments not
                            printed herewith.</note> bearing; on the subject accompany this
                        instruction. From these you will be able to gather ample arguments <pb facs="0612" n="478" xml:id="pg_478"/> to show that such a prohibition as
                        is foreshadowed would be utterly needless and a harmful blow at the
                        increasing trade relations between the United States and Denmark which we
                        are so desirous to foster.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">T. F.
                            Bayard.</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
